the left iliac fossa.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA CT scan is performed and shows diverticulae in the sigmoid colon with some surrounding fat stranding. There are no other abnormalities apart from a 5 cm para-oesophageal hiatus hernia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"With regard to the hiatus hernia, which one of the following is the most appropriate advice?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Further assessment with a barium meal","This CT finding is incidental","Prescribe esomeprazole","Repeat scan in 12 months","Further assessment by endoscopy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMost hiatus hernias - including large para-oesophageal hernias - do not cause significant symptoms. If the patient had reflux symptoms, an endoscopy might be appropriate. Symptoms of early satiety or obstruction - which could be due to a large para-oesophageal hernia - might also lead to an endoscopy. If further investigations are indicated, large para-oesophageal hernias are better defined with a contrast study. Esomeprazole is not indicated in an asymptomatic patient and carries additional risk of infection and other side effects. In this case, the patient does not need any further investigation or management of the hernia, which is almost certainly an \u003Cstrong\u003Eincidental finding and can be ignored\u003C/strong\u003E. Obviously the CT findings should be discussed with the patient and reassurance given that this incidental finding is of no clinical significance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the patient was experiencing upper abdominal symptoms, then a contrast study or endoscopy could be considered. Prescribing esomeprazole is not going to be of any value and repeating the CT scan in 12 months will only show similar findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe cause of her pain will be diverticulitis as described in the CT findings. This will be managed with analgesics as required and review.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most para-oesophageal hernias do not produce symptoms of any consequence."],"references":["Roman S, Kahrilas P. The diagnosis and management of hiatus hernia. BMJ. 2014. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25341679/","Jaynes M, Kumar AB. The risks of long-term use of proton pump inhibitors: a critical review.\u00a0Ther Adv Drug Saf. 2018. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6463334/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83924"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"403"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83924","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83924"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-02T09:35:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-02T09:36:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"403"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101485"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"grou